Recently, the anti-epidemic materials sent by Japan are frequently quoted in the Buddhist scriptures —— from the book of songs, the Qin wind and no clothes, from the book of songs, and from the Book of Songs, the Book of Songs, the Book of Songs, the Book of Songs, the Book of Songs, the Book of songs, the latest batch of materials quotes a line from the Tang dynasty poet Wang Changling's Song of sending firewood to serve the emperor: "Qingshan and he Zeng are fishing in the same cloud and rain, he is fishing in the moon. " She even wrote a poem called "Tongqi Lianzhi" from "a thousand words" -- "Liao River is melting with snow and blooming with flowers; Tongqi Lianzhi looks forward to spring. "

Japan's aid to Wuhan

↓

The mountains and rivers are different, the wind and the moon are the same day

In an interview with thepaper.cn, Deng Xiaojun, a professor of literature at Capital Normal University and professor of ancient Chinese literature, said: 'The Japanese President, Jianzhen, has made thousands of cassocks to perform Chinese famous virtues and various monks, on the edge of his cassock were embroidered four stanzas "the mountains and rivers are foreign, the wind and the moon are of the same sky. " It is obvious that this Gatha had a profound effect on Jianzhen's willingness to go east to Japan to spread Buddhism. Gatha is a poem, a Buddhist poem. "Mountains and rivers, the same day, " the poem said Japan, China, although mountains and rivers of land, are different countries, but Qingfengmingyue, our two peoples wear the same day. Below, "to the Buddha, a common origin" , poetry message to all the Chinese Buddha, a common conclusion of the future of good Karma.

"Now, when the Chinese people are suffering from the plague of COVID-19 pneumonia, Japan has sent them precious medical supplies. Under the packaging label, the eight Chinese characters are written: 'mountains and Rivers, foreign lands, Wind and moon, the same day' , which not only embody the millennium friendship between the Chinese and Japanese people since the King of Longhouse and Jianzhen, but also express, in the rhetoric of Xiehouzi, the hope of sending a message to the Chinese people, the hope of sending a message to the Chinese people, the hope of sending a message to the Chinese people, the hope of the Japanese people for Friendship with the Chinese people at this moment, " professor Deng Xiaojun said.

Japan's aid to Hubei

How shall it be said that you have no clothes ? I will share my lower garments with you 

This old saying comes from more than 3,000 years ago, plain and sonorous. "It is not said no clothes, son with the same robe" from the "book of Songs" in the "state wind Qin Feng no clothes" .

How shall it be said that you have no clothes ? I will share my long robes with you . The King is raising his forces ; I will prepare my lance and spear , And will be your comrade ! How shall it be said that you have no clothes ? I will share my under clothes with you . The King is raising his forces ; I will prepare my spear and Lance , And will take the field with you ! How shall it be said that you have no clothes ? I will share my lower garments with you . The King is raising his forces ; I will prepare my buffcoat and sharp weapons , And will march along with you .

When we quote it today, we give it a sense of "solidarity and morale. ".

Japan's aid to Dalian

Castle Peak Road with clouds and rain, ming he was two fishing fishing

This poem is from Wang Changling's The servant who delivers the firewood, the poem reads, "when Yuan River meets Wugang on the river, you will never feel the pain of leaving him; when mountains and mountains share the same clouds and rain, the moon has never been a two-country country country. " It is the profound friendship between two people who share the same place and the same heart.

Japan's aid to Liaoning

Liao River Snow Melt, rich flowers bloom; together with gas and branches, a total of hope for spring

Toyama Prefecture donated 10,000 masks to Liaoning Province on Sunday, while a box filled with masks was printed with the words: "Snow melts in Liao River, flowers bloom in Toyama; together we hope for spring. " This poem quotes a thousand words written by Liang Zhou Xingsi in the southern dynasty: "The brothers Kong Huai, together with Qi Lianzhi. Make friends and share points, cut and grind the precepts. " "Tongqi Lianzhi" refers to the brothers and sisters of one's countrymen.

The Japanese newspaper Asahi Shimbun also said the poem meant both sides were looking forward to the arrival of spring. "I know there is an urgent need for masks, " said Yuichi Sakuri, director of Toyama Prefecture's General Policy Bureau. "people in Liaoning Province are facing difficulties and we will support them. "

In contrast to these profound and emotional verses from Chinese classical literature, "Go Wuhan" , which we repeat over and over again as a slogan, seems a little barren.

When the country is in danger, perhaps it is not polite to express feelings, but at the critical moment of survival, if there is no "I smile to the sky from across the knife, to leave the liver and Gallbladder Two Kunlun" , and if there is no "I don't look at the cold star, I recommend the shaft with my blood" , many people's stories should be passed on how long, and how much less heroic.

As one scholar put it, the poems "caught fire at the wrong time, but at the right time, " which might be a good point for us to think about how our own culture has left us at a loss for words while others talk.
